postcontent: This pistol was one of only three handguns ever to be mass produced by the original Springfield Armory. Total production was 4,021. This is serial #1. There were probably some made before this one to be given to calvary officers to "beta test". Pistol used the Maynard tape system, which was found to have issues in wet weather. (The Maynard tape system was copied and used in kid's cap guns) Pistol has a 12 inch rifled barrel. Lock reads "1856" rear of the hammer. The primer tape door bears the federal eagle, and forward of the tape door is marked "U.S. Springfield". "1" is stamped on the back of the brass bolster on the butt of the pistol. There is a military cartouche on the right side of the stock. Unfortunately, I do not have the removable butt-stock. If I did it would be worth twice as much. title: For Sale:  WWI 8mm Revolver
postcontent:
Manufactured in Spain by Tracaola, Aranzabal, Y Cia for the French military in WWI when French arms makers couldn't keep up with military demand for pistols. The factory record of serial numbers were destroyed in the war, but all historical accounts put this revolver at either late-1915 or early-1916. This is not a replica. This is a WWI infantry-issued service pistol that's still 100% functional and actually in really good condition for being 101-102 years old. 
This is chambered in 8mm Lebel Revolver, and I'm including a bit of brass and the dies to go with it. The bullets are readily available on most large supply sites or directly from Fiochi. If you don't reload, the ammo itself is offered in limited runs every two years on Midway, Ammoseek, BuffaloArms, and GrafAmmo. The other option is to go with .32-20 rounds, which chamber and fire just fine, but aren't historically accurate. I'm including some .32-20 brass as well.
 
Here's the history on this gun if you're curious; http://www.forgottenweapons.com/eibar-spanish-model-92-revolver/
